Using the Bloomberg Terminal to Explore Stock Market Trends: An Analysis of Historical EPS Forecast Accuracy for All Firms in the 2019 S&P 500 Index¶

by Marc Angelo Acebedo¶

Investigation Overview¶

Through using Bloomberg Excel functions, I gathered the following 4 stock price data for all firms in the 2019 S&P Index from 1999 - 2019:

  • Actual EPS
  • Forecasted EPS
  • EOD Price
  • Forecasted EPS (made 3 months prior)

For a broad picture, I wanted to examine the accuracy between forecasted EPS to their corresponding actual EPS values.

Dataset Overview¶

The main dataset, features.csv, consists of 167,660 entries with 5 columns.

The other dataset in question, avgs.csv, contains 52,015 with 5 columns.

The quantitative values in this dataset consist of yearly, quarterly, and twenty-year averages extracted from the previous features.csv dataset.

Lastly, firms.csv assigns each firm abbreviation with firm ID as the primary key.

Question 2¶

I generate naive EPS forecasts by calculating the rolling mean of the 2 actual EPS values from the past 2 quarters. How do my EPS forecasts compare to Bloomberg's EPS forecasts?

In [11]:
Image(PATH_MULTIVARIATE + 'blmbrg-naive-pred-term.png')
Out[11]:

Observation 1: There are 2 notable terms regarding Bloomberg EPS forecasts: 2008Q4 and 2000Q4. Bloomberg forecasters were overly optimistic in 2008Q4, while overly pessimistic in 2000Q4.

Observation 2: There are 4 notable terms regarding my naive EPS forecasts: 2000Q4, 2001Q, 2008Q4, and 2009Q1.

  • My naive forecasts tended to be overly optimistic in 2001Q1 and 2000Q4 (the latter being consistent with the Bloomberg forecasts
  • My naive forecasts tended to be overly pessimistic in 2000Q4 and 2001Q1

Observation 3: From 2012Q3 onwards, my average naive prediction errors stay closer to 0 than the Bloomberg prediction errors do.

Average Bloomberg prediction errors tend to be lesser than the naive forecasts from that period, veering away from 0. This means that in the more recent years since 2012, Bloomberg EPS forecasts were less accurate than my own naive forecasts.

Observation 4: My average naive forecasts and Bloomberg forecasts both roughly "equalize", following the same trend "clustering" around 0, from 2003Q4 to 2007Q4.

Observation 5: Look at 2000Q4 and 2001Q4. In the former, my naive forecasts tend to be overly pessimistic, then turn overly optimistic in the quarter immediately after.

Observation 6: Look at 2008Q4 and 2009Q1, where the previous pattern is reversed. In the former, my naive forecasts tend to be overly optimistic, then become overly pessimistic in the quarter immediately after.

Expanding from the previous 2 observations, it seems that my naive prediction errors change "mood" when entering a new year from 2000 to 2001 and 2008 to 2009.

  • An interesting note: my naive forecasts spiked in pessimism during 2009Q1: only right before the Great Recession began to recover in June of 2009.
  • Another interesting note: Bloomberg forecasters tended to be overly optimistic in their EPS forecasts during the "harder" years of the bear market.

Observation 2: Overall, my naive forecasts tend to be more accurate and better-fitting than Bloomberg forecasts across all years.

In Q2, the average prediction errors for both Bloomberg and naive forecasts "split up" into separate directions.

Observation 3: In Q4 across all years, both forecast types tended to be more optimistic. This makes intuitive sense.

Observation 4: These results are consistent with the first visual, where Bloomberg forecasts have been overly optimistic during 2000Q4 and 2008Q4: both outliers occur during the same quarter at Q4.
